06142nam a22008775i 9780231527071DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20102010nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2010022971  a97802315270717 a10.7312/wall151562doi  a(DE-B1597)459420  a(OCoLC)979574505  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBJ1461.T293bF38 2011 7aPHI0070002bisacsh04a1232221 aWallace, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFate, Time, and Language :bAn Essay on Free Will /cDavid Wallace; ed. by Steven Cahn, Maureen Eckert. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tINTRODUCTION -- tPART I. THE BACKGROUND -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. FATALISM -- t2. PROFESSOR TAYLOR ON FATALISM -- t3. FATALISM AND ABILITY -- t4. FATALISM AND ABILITY II -- t5. FATALISM AND LINGUISTIC REFORM -- t6. FATALISM AND PROFESSOR TAYLOR -- t7. TAYLOR’S FATAL FALLACY -- t8. A NOTE ON FATALISM -- t9. TAUTOLOGY AND FATALISM -- t10. FATALISTIC ARGUMENTS -- t11. COMMENT -- t12. FATALISM AND ORDINARY LANGUAGE -- t13. FALLACIES IN TAYLOR’S “FATALISM” -- tPART II. THE ESSAY -- t14. RENEWING THE FATALIST CONVERSATION -- t15. RICHARD TAYLOR’S “FATALISM” AND THE SEMANTICS OF PHYSICAL MODALITY -- tPART III. EPILOGUE -- t16. DAVID FOSTER WALLACE AS STUDENT: A MEMOIR -- tAPPENDIX: THE PROBLEM OF FUTURE CONTINGENCIES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1962, the philosopher Richard Taylor used six commonly accepted presuppositions to imply that human beings have no control over the future. David Foster Wallace not only took issue with Taylor's method, which, according to him, scrambled the relations of logic, language, and the physical world, but also noted a semantic trick at the heart of Taylor's argument.Fate, Time, and Language presents Wallace's brilliant critique of Taylor's work. Written long before the publication of his fiction and essays, Wallace's thesis reveals his great skepticism of abstract thinking made to function as a negation of something more genuine and real. He was especially suspicious of certain paradigms of thought-the cerebral aestheticism of modernism, the clever gimmickry of postmodernism-that abandoned "the very old traditional human verities that have to do with spirituality and emotion and community." As Wallace rises to meet the challenge to free will presented by Taylor, we witness the developing perspective of this major novelist, along with his struggle to establish solid logical ground for his convictions. This volume, edited by Steven M. Cahn and Maureen Eckert, reproduces Taylor's original article and other works on fatalism cited by Wallace. James Ryerson's introduction connects Wallace's early philosophical work to the themes and explorations of his later fiction, and Jay Garfield supplies a critical biographical epilogue.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFate and fatalism. 0aSemantics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Free Will & Determinism.2bisacsh1 aAbelson, Raziel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAune, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Charles D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCahn, Steven M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCahn, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCahn, Steven, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEckert, Maureen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckert, Maureen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/